## 3. Design Considerations

### 3.1 Design Assumptions

| ID | Assumption | Justification |
|---|---|---|
| DA-01 | A typical user logs **3–8 entries/day** | Comparable health-journaling apps |
| DA-02 | Average chat message: **20–40 words** | Casual journaling tone |
| DA-03 | Read-to-write ratio on log data: **~5:1** | Dashboard re-reads dominate |
| DA-04 | Peak concurrency v1.0: **≤10,000** (NFR-03) | Stated in SRS |
| DA-05 | ≥70% of users interact via Android | Pakistan market share |
| DA-06 | NLP intent confidence ≥80% achievable for English on common foods | Validated on Gemini 1.5 Flash with system prompt tuning |

### 3.2 Design Constraints

1. **Stateless Backend Tier** — to enable horizontal scaling per NFR-03, application servers hold no session-affine state; sessions live in Redis or as JWTs.
2. **Single Source of Truth** — MongoDB is authoritative for all persisted entities; Redis is a volatile cache only.
3. **NLP Provider Abstraction** — Gemini and OpenAI are interchangeable behind a `LLMProvider` strategy interface — switch cost must remain low.
4. **Mobile-First** — backend response envelopes are designed for mobile bandwidth (compact, paginated, optionally delta-encoded).
5. **Health Data Isolation** — health logs live in a logically separated collection with field-level encryption for sensitive symptom data.

### 3.3 Design Methodology

The team adopts **Agile / Scrum-lite** with **two-week sprints**, justified below:

| Approach | Pros | Cons | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|
| Waterfall | Predictable milestones | Inflexible to NLP iteration | ❌ Rejected |
| **Scrum-lite (chosen)** | Iterative; demo-driven; lightweight ceremonies | Requires discipline | ✅ **Adopted** |
| Pure Scrum | Maximum agility | Excess overhead for small team | ❌ Rejected |
| Kanban | Continuous flow | Poor fit for academic milestone reporting | ❌ Rejected |

Each sprint produces a **vertical slice** (e.g., Sprint 3 = "log a meal end-to-end with NLP and view it in the timeline"), maximising demonstrability.

### 3.4 Risks & Mitigation Strategies

| Risk ID | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| R-01 | NLP misclassifies local foods (e.g., *halwa puri*) | High | Medium | Few-shot prompt with local food list; user can correct (FR-10, FR-11) |
| R-02 | Users mistake the app for medical advice | Medium | High | Persistent disclaimer; onboarding screen; legal copy reviewed |
| R-03 | Health-data breach | Low | Critical | TLS 1.3, AES-256 at rest (NFR-05/08), field-level encryption for symptoms, audit logging (NFR-10) |
| R-04 | NLP cost spike (token overuse) | Medium | Medium | Daily per-user message cap; `max_tokens` ceiling; usage dashboard |
| R-05 | LLM hallucinations on health questions | High | Medium | Strict system prompt; refuse-to-diagnose policy; intent gating |
| R-06 | Connectivity loss mid-journaling | High | Low | Offline outbox: queue messages locally, sync on reconnect |
| R-07 | Gender-sensitive content (PCOS) discomfort | Medium | Medium | Inclusive UX writing; in-app preference toggles |
| R-08 | Affiliate-link compliance / misleading product claims | Medium | High | Editorial review checklist; disclaimer labels (FR-24) |

